Mr Houghton - a relation on Mrs Berry's mother's side - supplied the workhouse with between 700 and 800 loaves daily, although a local newspaper report from an inspector at the time claimed it was 'so bad that we don't know how to eat it', the Sunday Times reports, although this was later retracted.

Mrs Berry, 79, also researched her paternal family and discovered that her great-great-great grandfather Christopher Berry was a printer and bookseller.

But after he was hit by bankruptcy in the 1811, his wife Mary and six of their children were sent to the workhouse.

Only two of the children - her great, great grandmother, also called Mary, and Chris - were spared the workhouse.

